94—135 : well first the mind, animus or mens, is a part of man, as much as the foot or head: some deny this and affirm the mind’s sense to be a harmony or certain life-giving state of the body by which we have sense, though the mind is nowhere: they are quite wrong3 for often the body is sick, while the mind is happy 3 the mind is wretched, when the body is well3 just as the foot may be sore, when the head is whole: again the body is often asleep and without sense, while something in us is moved by various passions.
